entry.title: Prerender: Override user agent for prerendering on WebView
entry.content:
According to [1], navigation on WebView always enables user agent

override, but prerendering navigation doesn't set an override option and

fails DCHECK on activation due to the parameter mismatch (see the

associated issue).



This CL allows AwWebContentsDelegate to set the option. Android Chrome

with the desktop mode has a similar issue (https://crbug.com/1406149)

but this CL only fixes the WebView case for now.



Note that prerendering on WebView is an experimental feature that is

still behind the feature flag (kWebViewPrerender2).



[1]https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:android_webview/java/src/org/chromium/android_webview/AwContents.java;l=2564-2566;drc=3cc22c22d7637bc5604e8fef3b0882b51a762901

entry.title: [bfcache] Update NotRestoredReasons to match the spec draft
entry.content:
This CL updates NotRestoredReasons API's implementation to conform to the spec draft[1].

Namely, this CL

(1) removes "preventedBFCache" enum,

(2) adds "masked" to the outermost main frame when cross-origin iframes are blocking, and

(3) creates NotRestoredReasonDetails class on the blink side to make the reason into a struct like {"reason": "error-document"}.



As for (2), when `kAllowCrossOriginSubframes` flag is on, we add "masked" to the randomly selected cross-origin iframe.

Also with (2), `reasons` field is no longer specific to same-origin frames, so I'm moving the field out of `SameOriginDetails`.



We also need to add "masked" when UA internal reasons such as memory pressure block, and that's going to be addressed in a follow-up.



[1]: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9360/files

entry.title: cros-apps: hook up API availability check with Mojo binders
entry.content:
This CL hooks up ChromeOS Apps API availability check (e.g. is the frame

coming from an allowlisted origin) with the API info registry.



This CL introduces a `CrosAppsApiFrameContext` to help unifying the

API availability check logic for frame navigation and for Mojo binder.



As a result:

- We only register the Mojo binder on RFH if the RFH's profile supports

the API (e.g. base::Feature is enabled)

- Inside the binder, only run the binder if the RFH indeed has access

to the API (e.g. by matching against an allowlist)

entry.title: Split synced UserDisplayMode into CrOS and non-CrOS values
entry.content:
The existing "user_display_mode" synced value is renamed to

"user_display_mode_non_cros" and a new "user_display_mode_cros" value

is added.



This fixes an issue where apps installed on CrOS could cause apps

already installed on Win/Mac/Linux to change to open in a different

display mode (browser tab vs standalone window). Now, installing an app

or changing the user's display mode setting on CrOS will only affect the

setting on other CrOS devices (and non-CrOS devices only affect non-CrOS

devices).



This is also a migration: if an app is loaded and its UserDisplayMode

value is unset for the current platform (CrOS or non-CrOS), we import

a UDM value from the other platform (falling back to kStandalone if no

value is set at all) and store it back into the sync data.

3. Fixing a case where the code was using

entry.title: [text-spacing-trim] Relax fullwidth check
entry.content:
This patch changes `HanKerning::FontData` to check glyph

bounding box against its advances, not against `1ch`.



Under specific scale, some fonts may return advances of CJK

fullwidth punctuation characters slightly different from the

`1ch` (the advance of U+0x6C34).



Also some fonts are known to have narrower CJK fullwidth

punctuation characters than `1ch`, though they have enough

space to apply kerning[1].



This patch makes these cases applicable, as long as:

* The font has `halt` feature, claiming it can apply kerning.

* Each group of characters have the same advances.

* Characters that have language-dependent conventions have

enough internal space to apply kerning.



[1] https://github.com/kojiishi/east_asian_spacing/issues/175

entry.title: [MemoryCache] Add simple LRU based strong reference cache
entry.content:
- Introduce a bounded LRU based on a LinkedListHashSet. The head contains the item to evict first, and the tail has the most recently accessed item. The total size is bounded by a finch field trial flag,

so any increase in PMF from previous studies should be addressed.

- Remove kMemoryCacheStrongReferenceSingleUnload feature. All pages

was shown to be more useful.

- Introduce kResourceFetcherStoresStrongReferences feature. So we can

see if the bounded LRU is good enough instead of storing all references on the ResourceFetchers.

- Blink.MemoryCache.RevalidationPolicy.* counts were previously

counted for non-main thread loads which was incorrect since the

MemoryCache does not apply to non-main threads so exclude them from

the count

entry.title: Remove 1 overload of deprecated `base::Hash` function.
entry.content:
This CL replaces the callers of the removed overload with calls to

either `base::FastHash` or `base::PersistentHash`:



* `base/hash/hash_unittest.cc` - calling `PersistentHash` to preserve

the old behavior (`Hash` forwards to `PersistentHash`).

* `components/services/heap_profiling/allocation.cc` - calling

`FastHash`. `AllocationSite::Hash` is used as a hasher of

`std::unordered_map`.

* `components/viz/service/display/overlay_candidate_factory.cc` -

calling `FastHash`:

* This is consistent with another, preexisting setter of the

`tracking_id` field in the same source file

* It seems that this hash is not persisted and is only used

for comparison operators in `ProposedCandidateKey`

* A narrowing conversion has been made explicit in this CL

(this conversion already existed in one of the preexisting setters

of the `tracking_id` field)

* `components/viz/service/display/overlay_proposed_candidate.h` -

calling `FastHash`. `ProposedCandidateKeyHasher` is only used

as a hasher of `std::unordered_map`.

* `gpu/command_buffer/service/gr_shader_cache.cc` - calling `FastHash`.

It seems that `CacheKeyHash` is only used as a hasher of

`base::HashingLRUCache`.

* `ppapi/tools/pepper_hash_for_uma.cc` - calling `PersistentHash` to

preserve the old behavior, because the comment in that file suggests

that the hash may be compared with data in `histograms.xml` files.

entry.title: Implement "json" fetch destination for JSON module scripts
entry.content:
This patch adds a new `json` fetch destination [fetch-spec-pr], that has

the following characteristics:

- it implies the `Accept: application/json,*/*;q=0.5` HTTP header;

- it uses the `connect-src` CSP directive [csp-spec-pr].



This new destination is used when fetching JSON module scripts, using

range.

candidate window.

entry.title: [gtm] Fix the crash when opening the browser with empty new task
entry.content:
The crash happens because the SaveTask callback is called when opening

the browser and commit the textfield. The callback deletes the whole

task view where the child textfield is still stored in the focus

manager. This cl fixes that by tracking if the native window is

closing. If so, leave the view hierarchy clean up to the native

widget instead of manually deleting the view since it will refresh

the next time the glanceables is opened.

entry.title: Fix install timestamp of command-line extensions in telemetry reports
entry.content:
The extension telemetry service reports the install timestamp of a

command-line extension as 0. The 0 value indicates that the

extension is not actually installed because command-line loads

are disabled for Enhanced Safe Browsing (ESB) opted-in users.



This CL fixes an edge-case where the command-line extension had

previously been installed, for example when ESB was disabled. When

ESB is enabled, the telemetry service reported this previous install

timestamp instead of 0. This CL ensures that the service reports an

install timestamp of 0 always.

entry.title: [grid] Downgrade flex fraction logic to floats (instead of doubles).
entry.content:
Previously we had a separate struct for representing fr-units called

GridLengths. This stored a Length, and then separately a double for

fr units.



In:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4815886



I merged these two objects, however this left us storing fr's as

floats, but performing operations as doubles. This resulted in sutble

numerical errors when converting between them.



To remove the conversions, use floats within the grid logic instead.



The primary risk of this patch is the loss of precision, however this

seems unlikely in real world usages.

entry.title: Use `span` instead of ptr+len pair as param of `base::Hash` function.
entry.content:
`base::Hash` has the following 2 overloads:



```

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(const void* data, size_t length);

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(const std::string& str);

```



This CL replaces the 1st overload with:



```

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(base::span data);

```



`base::Hash` is a deprecated function that in the long-term should be

replaced with either 1) `base::FastHash` (result can vary when launching

Chrome or tests another time) or 2) `base::PersistentHash` (same result

every time forever). Deprecation is tracked in

https://crbug.com/1025358. To minimize risk and amount of changes this

CL preserves the old behavior (i.e. continues to use the deprecated

`base::Hash`) and the removal will be attempted in a separate WIP CL at

https://crrev.com/c/5206108.
